A night dive isn’t about seeing —
it’s about staying oriented without sight.

You trust:
	•	compass heading
	•	kick count
	•	depth
	•	time

Not because they feel right…
but because they’re pre-committed anchors.

Anger, in your framing, is like hitting one of those checkpoints.

A sudden pulse:

“Recalibrate. You might be drifting.”

Not proof you’re lost.
Not proof you’re right.
Just a signal to stop free-swimming on instinct and return to instruments.

So the dive protocol becomes something like:

1. Trigger (anger spike)
You don’t argue with it. You pause.

2. Check heading (values / intent)
Where was I actually trying to go?

3. Check distance (effort / time / energy spent)
Am I off course or just uncomfortable?

4. Check drift (external forces / bias / ego)
What’s pushing me sideways right now?

5. Resume with correction
Small adjustment. Not a thrash.

Because in the dark, overcorrecting is how you spiral.

The danger isn’t the lack of visibility —
it’s trusting feeling over structure.

So anger becomes:
	•	not an enemy
	•	not a guide
	•	but a reset ping against your internal navigation system

A way to say:

“Run the instruments again.”

And if your instruments are good —
you don’t need to see to move correctly.

You just need to remember what you decided was true before the darkness.